 backends, logging/metrics sinks, network/egress) is designed. Now we need to deep-dive into the **pipeline and composition layer** that sits on top of it.\n\n**What exists**: Architecture docs at `/home/kadajett/prism-pipe/ARCHITECTURE.md` and `/home/kadajett/prism-pipe/docs/DEEP-DIVE-INGRESS-AND-COMPOSITION.md` with detailed designs for:\n- Middleware pipeline (Koa-style `ctx + next()`)\n- Agent composition (chain, fork-join, thinking-wrapper, tool-router)\n- Timeout budgets that decrement across composed steps\n- Canonical data format for cross-provider transforms (OpenAI ↔ Anthropic ↔ Google ↔ Ollama)\n- Error taxonomy and per-step error policies\n- Cost accounting across multi-agent requests including flat-rate subscriptions\n\n**What we need researched**:\n1. Review the current architecture docs and identify gaps, contradictions, or over-engineering\n2. Research how existing tools (LiteLLM, Portkey, Martian, AI Gateway by Cloudflare) handle the same problems — what works, what's painful, what's missing\n3. Propose concrete TypeScript interfaces for the pipeline engine, composition engine, and transform registry\n4. Identify the minimal set of middleware needed for v0.1 vs what can wait\n5. Research streaming (SSE) composition — can we stream intermediate steps or only the final output? How do LiteLLM/Portkey handle this?\n6. Evaluate whether Express middleware is sufficient or if we need a custom pipeline engine on top\n\n**Constraints**: TypeScript, Biome, Express, must run on Node.js 20+ and degrade gracefully on edge runtimes (no worker_threads). SQLite default storage.\n\n**Repo**: `/home/kadajett/prism-pipe`\n\n## Focus Areas\n- competitive analysis (LiteLLM, Portkey, Martian, CF AI Gateway)\n- TypeScript interface design for pipeline/composition\n- SSE streaming in composed multi-agent requests\n- minimal v0.1 scope vs future phases","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Kadajett/prism-pipe/issues/1/reactions","total_count":1,"+1":0,"-1":0,"la